.\" cligPart OPTIONS
.SH OPTIONS
.IP -ncpus
Number of processors to use with OpenMP,
.br
1 Int value between 1 and oo.
.br
Default: `1'
.IP -o
Root of the output file names,
.br
1 String value
.IP -filterbank
Raw data in SIGPROC filterbank format.
.IP -psrfits
Raw data in PSRFITS format.
.IP -noweights
Do not apply PSRFITS weights.
.IP -noscales
Do not apply PSRFITS scales.
.IP -nooffsets
Do not apply PSRFITS offsets.
.IP -topo
Fold the data topocentrically (i.e. don't barycenter).
.IP -invert
For rawdata, flip (or invert) the band.
.IP -zerodm
Subtract the mean of all channels from each sample (i.e. remove zero DM).
.IP -samples
Treat the data as samples and not as finite-duration integrated data.
.IP -normalize
Bandpass flatten the data by normalizing the subbands.
.IP -if
A specific IF to use if available (summed IFs is the default),
.br
1 Int value between 0 and 1.
.IP -clip
Time-domain sigma to use for clipping (0.0 = no clipping, 6.0 = default,
.br
1 Float value between 0 and 1000.0.
.br
Default: `6.0'
.IP -noclip
Do not clip the data.  (The default is to _always_ clip!).
.IP -noxwin
Do not show the result plots on-screen, only make postscript files.
.IP -runavg
Subtract each blocks average as it is read (single channel data only).
.IP -fine
A finer gridding in the p/pdot plane (for well known p and pdot).
.IP -coarse
A coarser gridding in the p/pdot plane (for uknown p and pdot).
.IP -slow
Sets useful flags for slow pulsars.
.IP -searchpdd
Search p-dotdots as well as p and p-dots.
.IP -searchfdd
Search f-dotdots as well as f and f-dots.
.IP -nosearch
Show but do not search the p/pdot and/or DM phase spaces.
.IP -nopsearch
Show but do not search over period.
.IP -nopdsearch
Show but do not search over p-dot.
.IP -nodmsearch
Show but do not search over DM.
.IP -scaleparts
Scale the part profiles independently.
.IP -allgrey
Make all the images greyscale instead of color.
.IP -fixchi
Adjust the reduced chi^2 values so that off-pulse reduced chi^2 = 1.
.IP -justprofs
Only output the profile portions of the plot.
.IP -n
Profile bins applied to ALL candidates (default: chosen automatically per candidate from its period),
.br
1 Int value.
.IP -nsub
The number of sub-bands to use for the DM search.  If unspecified, will use something reasonable.,
.br
1 Int value between 1 and 4096.
.IP -npart
The number of sub-integrations to use for the period search,
.br
1 Int value between 1 and 4096.
.br
Default: `64'
.IP -pstep
The minimum period stepsize over the observation in profile bins,
.br
1 Int value between 1 and 10.
.br
Default: `2'
.IP -pdstep
The minimum P-dot stepsize over the observation in profile bins,
.br
1 Int value between 1 and 20.
.br
Default: `4'
.IP -dmstep
The minimum DM stepsize over the observation in profile bins,
.br
1 Int value between 1 and 10.
.br
Default: `2'
.IP -npfact
2 * npfact * proflen + 1 periods and p-dots will be searched,
.br
1 Int value between 1 and 10.
.br
Default: `2'
.IP -ndmfact
2 * ndmfact * proflen + 1 DMs will be searched,
.br
1 Int value between 1 and 1000.
.br
Default: `3'
.IP -phs
Offset phase for the profil,
.br
1 Double value between 0.0 and 1.0.
.br
Default: `0.0'
.IP -start
The folding start time as a fraction of the full obs,
.br
1 Double value between 0.0 and 1.0.
.br
Default: `0.0'
.IP -end
The folding end time as a fraction of the full obs,
.br
1 Double value between 0.0 and 1.0.
.br
Default: `1.0'
.IP -mask
File containing masking information to use,
.br
1 String value
.IP -ignorechan
Comma separated string (no spaces!) of channels to ignore (or file containing such string).  Ranges are specified by min:max[:step],
.br
1 String value
.IP -candfile
Text file listing candidates to fold (one per line; header line starts with #),
.br
1 String value
.IP infile
Input data file name.  Must be raw radio data (PSRFITS or SIGPROC filterbank) or PRESTO subbands (*.subNN); already-dedispersed .dat time series and event files are not supported (no per-candidate DM).
.\" cligPart OPTIONS end

.\" cligPart DESCRIPTION
.SH DESCRIPTION
prepfold_multi folds many pulsar candidates -- each with its own
period/frequency, spin derivatives, and DM -- in a single pass over
the raw data.  Ordinary
.BR prepfold (1)
folds one candidate per invocation, so searching N candidates means
reading the raw data N times.  prepfold_multi instead reads and cleans
each raw block exactly once (the "read-once" half of its
read-once/dedisperse-many strategy), then dedisperses and folds that
block for every candidate in the list (the "dedisperse-many" half)
before moving on to the next block.  The expensive resource -- raw-data
disk I/O -- is therefore paid once no matter how many candidates are
folded.

Because every candidate already supplies its own DM and spin
parameters via the
.B -candfile
(see CANDIDATE FILE FORMAT below), prepfold_multi has no single-candidate
spin (-p/-pd/-pdd/-f/-fd/-fdd), source (-psr/-par/-polycos/-timing),
binary (-bin and friends), or event (-events/-days/-mjds/-double/-offset)
options: those are meaningless when many independent candidates are
folded in one run.  Likewise prepfold_multi only accepts raw radio data
or PRESTO subbands as input, never an already-dedispersed time series
or event file, because there is no single DM to apply to a .dat file
on behalf of several candidates at once (see "Rest infile" above and
CANDIDATE FILE FORMAT below).

All of the fold mathematics is shared with
.BR prepfold (1)
(the same dedispersion, folding, optimization, and plotting code), so a
prepfold_multi fold of one candidate reproduces the corresponding
single-candidate
.B prepfold
run field for field.

The per-candidate loop (folding, optimizing, and writing each
candidate's output) is parallelized with OpenMP; use
.B -ncpus
to set the number of threads.  Per-candidate results are bit-identical
regardless of how many threads are used -- -ncpus only changes how many
candidates are processed concurrently, never the arithmetic performed
for any one of them.
.\" cligPart DESCRIPTION end

.SH "CANDIDATE FILE FORMAT"
The file given to
.B -candfile
is a whitespace/tab-separated text table, one candidate per row.

The first non-blank line is the
.I header
and must begin with `#', followed by one or more column keys separated
by whitespace.  Column keys are case-insensitive.  Recognized keys are:
.TP
.B name
Optional.  The candidate's name, used to build its output filenames
(.pfd, .bestprof, etc.), exactly as the corresponding
.B prepfold
options would.  If omitted, an output name is autogenerated from the
candidate's period or frequency, exactly as
.B prepfold
autogenerates names for candidates given via -p/-f.  If two candidates
would resolve to the same name (two unnamed candidates with the same
period, or two rows with the same explicit
.BR name ),
prepfold_multi disambiguates the later one with a `_2', `_3', ...
suffix and prints a warning, rather than letting one candidate's
output silently clobber another's.
.TP
.B DM
Required.  The candidate's dispersion measure (cm^-3 pc).  Must be >= 0.
.TP
.B p
The candidate's folding period (s).  Must be > 0.  Selects
.I period
mode for the whole file (see below).
.TP
.B f
The candidate's folding frequency (Hz).  Must be > 0.  Selects
.I frequency
mode for the whole file (see below).
.TP
.B pd
Optional.  The period derivative (s/s).  Only valid in period mode.
.TP
.B pdd
Optional.  The period 2nd derivative (s/s^2).  Only valid in period mode.
.TP
.B fd
Optional.  The frequency derivative (Hz/s).  Only valid in frequency mode.
.TP
.B fdd
Optional.  The frequency 2nd derivative (Hz/s^2).  Only valid in frequency mode.
.PP
The header must contain exactly one of
.B p
or
.BR f ,
never both: this choice is file-wide and fixes whether every candidate
in the file is specified in period mode (p, optionally with pd/pdd) or
frequency mode (f, optionally with fd/fdd).  Mixing modes within one
file is rejected: a header may not combine
.B p
with
.B fd
or
.BR fdd ,
nor combine
.B f
with
.B pd
or
.BR pdd .
The header may declare at most 8 columns.

In the body of the file, blank lines and lines beginning with `#' are
ignored as comments.  Every other line is a data row and must supply
exactly as many whitespace-separated fields as the header declared,
in the same column order as the header.  Numeric fields (DM, p/f,
and any derivatives) are parsed like C's
.BR strtod (3),
so ordinary decimal and scientific notation (e.g.
.IR 8.66430621957513e-3 )
are both accepted.  DM must be >= 0 and the period (or frequency) must
be > 0 on every row, or prepfold_multi reports the offending line
number and exits before any folding begins.

Example (period mode, three candidates at nearby trial DMs, sharing one
spin solution -- see tests/prepfold/multi_cands.txt):
.RS
.nf
# name      DM      p                    pd
candDM238   238.30  8.66430621957513e-3  -5.01154755640048e-11
candDM240   240.30  8.66430621957513e-3  -5.01154755640048e-11
candDM242   242.30  8.66430621957513e-3  -5.01154755640048e-11
.fi
.RE

